g.title: Folded Corner.69
g.desc: Façade pattern compliments SRP on the subsystem level. Façade...

g.text: Façade pattern compliments SRP on the subsystem level. Façade decouples details from the client, by restricting them to a limited interface. Firstly, it provides more control over the execution flow of the software. More control will results in less unforeseen scenario’s, resulting in fewer bugs and thus stability. Secondly, the responsibility of the façade is shifted from the client to a dictated class. This enhances readability and reusability on client side. Readability, because code is ‘well’ separated. Reusability, because execution sequences can be shared across the code-base.

g.title: Folded Corner.97

g.text: The Façade pattern facilitates sub-system layering, by introducing an entry point to another layer. Each sub-system communicates to a single, limited interface of the other sub-system. This makes change and re-use easier. We can ‘swap’ sub-systems with less impact, because there is low coupling.

g.title: Folded Corner.138
g.desc: A well designed software sub-system will have multiple classe...

g.text: A well designed software sub-system will have multiple classes all serving a single responsibility. This results in multiple interfaces all around the sub-system. This can be ‘overwhelming’ and complex for clients, because clients are required to compose the correct instruction sequences of multiple objects them-self. The Façade pattern can help with unifying object interfaces as a goal to provide a simplified interface. I.e.: Façade facilitates an abstraction, by grouping objects of a sub-system, to provide a simplified interface to the client.

g.title: Folded Corner.189
g.desc: Restriction is a result of simplification. The Façade pattern...

g.text: Restriction is a result of simplification. The Façade pattern provides a limited, simplified interface to the client. Restriction prevents clients from interacting with the system in a ‘unforeseen’ way that might result in failure or damage to a system. The larger the interface of a system the harder it will become to oversee all possible error scenario’s. Restriction provides more control over execution.

g.title: Folded Corner.196
g.desc: The façade unifies sub-system classes. This unification can b...

g.text: The façade unifies sub-system classes. This unification can be identified as a ‘god’ like object. However, in the non-strict sense the Façade has one responsibility, namely to cluster and delegate object calls to simplify interfacing to a subsystem. However, we have to carefully monitor if the façade will not become the place to make quick and easy fixes by adding responsibilities there, because it is after all an unified ‘place’ where a lot of objects come together. A ‘God’ object is the inverse of SRP. It will be hard to introduce new changes, bring it under test and analyze problems.

g.title: Folded Corner.202
g.desc: Façade pattern compliments OCP. Façade decouples clients from...

g.text: Façade pattern compliments OCP. Façade decouples clients from low level details of a sub-system. Decoupling simplifies change in the lower level details of the sub-system without affecting clients. This has positive effect on the stability of production and test code; less recompilation and modification in existing code will be required.
